snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly, they could have revitalized the franchise by making this movie (and subsequent inevitable sequels) about John Connor sending agents/reprogrammed Terminators back in time, to save his future lieutenants, for the inevitable showdown, the defeat of Skynet. Make each movie about a different person that has to both survive a Terminator (or two), and then make it through Judgment Day alive.



And then throw a curveball in, when one lieutenant dies. The timeline changes, things start going wrong, and John and the surviving lieutenants have to piece together what went wrong, from past records, and notes, detailing the failed rescue, from other people John had sent back in time.



Because those people remember a past future (redundant, or contradictory? You decide!) that happened before the time travel shenanigans went sideways, and know who is missing. Then John has to make a choice, start from scratch with his grand rescue project, or try and send someone/something back, to try and fix the one mistake, risking further shenanigans in the timestream, from two different sets of rescuers going back, and running into each other?



If that sounds like a convoluted mess, and a potentially huge waste of time and money... You must be new to the Terminator series. Also, watch Dark Fate, and Genesys, and tell me how this idea is somehow worse.

T2- The protector who goes back in time is a machine.
DF- The protector who goes back in time is both human and a machine.

DF- The protagonist spends half the movie thinking she's the mother only to later find out that she is the saviour.


T1- Arnie's character is the bad guy.
T2- Arnie's character is the good guy.
DF- Arnie's character is first the bad guy and then later is the good guy.

snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly, this is the worst film that I can remember sitting all the way through. It's just a bargain bin version of Terminator 2, whose story makes Terminator 1 and 2 pointless. It borrows major plot points from Terminator 3, Salvation and Genisys, even though it retcons all three films. So it's a huge slap to the face of not only the fans of the series, but also the people who made all five of the previous films.
That's just the beginning of my criticism for this movie. The film itself was terrible, with terrible acting, too much CGI and absolutely no originality. The marketing campaign was nothing but identity politics, with one social media update going so far as to label people who wouldn't like it "misogynists". Look, Millennial Filipino-American immigrant Woman here, and I don't like it. I don't like it because it sucks, and I don't like it because it's a slap in the face as a fan of the series.
